Overview

In this section, we approach the EDA and data understanding by:

  1. Applying data engineering through a binning strategy as an alternate means to interpret certain features and for possible use in downstream models.
  2. Visually inspect distributions of categorical and numerical features in relation to churn using plotly
  3. Statistically examine their relationship with churn using pandas and statsmodels
  4. Understand collinearity between features using pandas and statsmodels
  5. Visually understand two high importance features and their relationship with churn using plotly

These steps allow us to reveal patterns, identify data quality issues, uncover relationships between varaibles, and help validate assumptions. Altogether they help form the foundation from which our modelling decisions will be made.

Imports and data load

# Import libraries
import plotly.express as px
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
import statsmodels.api as sm
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import os
# Load the data
project_path = os.getcwd()
df = pd.read_csv(project_path + "/Data/netflix_customer_churn.csv")
# Set the default template for plotly
import plotly.io as pio
pio.templates.default = "plotly_dark"
# Set plotly render to work with Quarto
pio.renderers.default = 'notebook_connected' # or 'notebook_connected'

Data description and engineering

In this dataset with 5,000 observations, a unit of observation represents a single subscriber’s information across: age, gender, subscription_type, watch_hours, last_login_days, region, device, monthly_fee, payment_method, number_of_profiles, avg_watch_time_per_day, and favorite_genre. Additionally, we have churned representing their churned status. Thanks to the sensibily named variables, for brevity we will forgo formal variable definitions.

Given the synthetic nature of the data and no other means to validate, a reasonable assumption we work with is that the usage data within this dataset is a weekly snapshot. For example, the median for watch_hours is 8 hours (a plausible amount of weekly watch hours) and no subscribers have watch hours over 110 hours (well within the 168 hours available in a 7 day week).

The dataset is clean with no missing values, which we can attribute to the great work of our hypothetical data engineering team.

Based on the observed characteristics of each feature, we proactively define our numerical and categorical columns so that they are treated as such in our analysis and modelling downstream. For example, monthly_fee, while technically numerical, is more meaningfully treated as a categorical given it contains only three possible values (8.99, 13.99, or 17.99).

# Create column name lists for reference
categorical_cols = ['gender', 'subscription_type', 'region', 'device', 'payment_method', 'favorite_genre', 'monthly_fee',  'number_of_profiles']
numerical_cols = ['age', 'watch_hours', 'last_login_days', 'avg_watch_time_per_day']

We additionally define three new categoricals that are binned versions of age, last_login_days, and watch_hours which align with groupings typical for understanding demographics and engagement.

# Create bins for age group (ie. age)
df['age_grp'] = pd.cut(df['age'], bins=[0, 18, 24, 34, 44, 54, 64, np.inf],
                        labels=['0-17', '18–24', '25–34', '35–44', '45–54', '55–64', '65+'])

# Create bins for last login group (ie. last_login_days)
df['last_login_grp'] = pd.cut(df['last_login_days'], bins=[0, 7, 14, 30, np.inf],
                        labels=['0-7', '7-14', '14-30', '30+'])

# Create bins for engagement level (ie. watch_hours)
df['engagement_grp'] = pd.cut(df['watch_hours'], bins=[0, 1, 5, 10, 20, 200],
                        labels=['Very Low', 'Low', 'Medium', 'High', 'Very High'])

Churn rate overview

Across categorical and numeric features, the key highlights can be summarized as follows for subscribers who churn versus those who do not. Churned subscribers:

  • Are more likely to be on a Basic plan (40% vs. 25%, see subscription_type, monthly_fee)
  • Use Crypto and Gift Card payments more often (50% vs. 32%, see payment_method)
  • Are more typically have 3 or less profiles created (66% vs. 40%, see number_of_profiles)
  • Frequently have not logged in for > 30 days (73% vs. 25%, see last_login_grp, last_login_days)
  • Have low or very low engagement with < 5 watch hours (60% vs. 11%, see engagement_grp, watch_hours)

This indicates that these features together can likely provide a meaningful ability to predict churn.

Setup with helper functions

To expediently produce visual plots of both our categorical and numerical features, their distributions, and their relationship against our target variable churned, we define two helper functions plot_category and plot_numeric that will allow us to loop through features and create appropriate plots automatically.

# Update column name lists for reference
categorical_cols = ['gender', 'subscription_type', 'region', 'device', 'payment_method', 'favorite_genre', 'monthly_fee',  'number_of_profiles']
categorical_cols = categorical_cols + ['age_grp', 'last_login_grp', 'engagement_grp']
# Make all categoricals of category data type
for category in categorical_cols:
    df[category] = df[category].astype("category")

Define function for plot of categorical variables against target

def plot_category(df, category, target):
    # Create a churn rate comparison between groups - histogram for categorical (no curve option in express)
    fig = px.histogram(df, x=category, color=target, histnorm="percent",
                    category_orders={category: df[category].cat.categories},
                    barmode='group', opacity=0.75,
                    title=f"{category} Distribution",
                    template="plotly_dark"          
                    )
    fig.update_layout(title_subtitle_text=f"by {target}, n=5000")
    fig.show()

Define function for plot of continuous variables against target

def plot_numeric(df, numeric, target):
    # Create a churn rate comparison between groups - violin plot for continuous
    fig = px.violin(df, x=numeric, color=target,
                    violinmode = 'overlay', # overlay or group
                    title=f"{numeric} Distribution",
                    template="plotly_dark")
    fig.update_layout(title_subtitle_text=f"by {target}, n=5000")
    fig.show()

EDA for categoricals

for category in categorical_cols:
    plot_category(df, category, "churned")

EDA for numeric

for numeric in numerical_cols:
    plot_numeric(df, numeric, "churned")

Feature explanatory power

To understand each feature’s explanatory power through more statistical means, we additionally examine both 1) pearson correlation coefficients of each feature against target and 2) the p-value of each feature from a logistic regression model.

Features correlated with churn:

  • last_login_days and watch_hours have high correlation (0.47 and -0.47 respectively)
  • avg_watch_time_per_day has moderate correlation (-0.27)
  • number_of_profiles, subscription_type, payment_method have minor correlation (between |0.05| and |0.12| depending on category)

Features with lowest p-values (p < 0.05 indicating regression coefficient significantly different than 0):

  • number_of_profiles
  • last_login_days
  • watch_hours
  • payment_method
  • avg_watch_time_per_day

In both approaches, we can validate that the same features we found important in our visual analysis is further corroborated as significant through verification with statistical methods. Notably, subscription_type was not found to be significant and this is reasonable as the correlation was not strong to begin with. If our features were standard scaled, we could also use the coefficients in the logistic regression as a means to understand relative importance.

Note that these approaches will only capture linear relationships as we don’t have any priors to suggest otherwise. However, any non-linear relationship should be quantified through other approaches such Distance Correlation or Rank-based Correlation.

Encode categoricals for analysis

We will first make dummy variables for the categorical features, using pd.get_dummies for expedience.

# Revert back to original categoricals before engineered categories 
categorical_cols = ['gender', 'subscription_type', 'region', 'device', 'payment_method', 'favorite_genre', 'monthly_fee',  'number_of_profiles']

# Create temporary new dataset with categorical values encoded
temp_df = df[numerical_cols]
for category in categorical_cols:
    dummy_df = pd.get_dummies(df[category], prefix=category, dtype=int, drop_first=True)
    temp_df = temp_df.merge(dummy_df, left_index=True, right_index=True)

Correlation with target

# Calculate the correlation
target_corr = temp_df.corrwith(df['churned']).to_frame(name="coef")

# Plot the correlation
fig = px.bar(target_corr, x='coef', color='coef',
            title=f"Feature correlation with target")
fig.update_layout(
    title_subtitle_text=f"No correlation = 0 while proximity to -1 (blue) or +1 (yellow) indicates strength <br>of linear relationship",
    yaxis={'categoryorder':'total ascending'})   
fig.show()

Regression coefficients

We apply logistic regression here as our target is a discrete dependent variable. Note that while typically EDA can be done before train/test split to understand relationship, the criteria for feature selection should be done after the split to mitigate risk of data leakage.

# Add the target to our encoded df
target = df['churned']
predictors = sm.add_constant(temp_df)

# Create regression
logit_model = sm.Logit(target, predictors).fit()
print(logit_model.summary())

Collinearity

To fully understand the independent contribution of each feature, we may want to identify any collinearity between features.

This could allow us identify and remove a highly collinear feature to simplify the models we build and make coefficients easier to interpret. However, if the primary objective is to make accurate predictions, the model might still perform well with collinear features.

We will examine collinearity with two methods: 1) correlation matrix and 2) variance inflation factor (VIF).

Like our previous section on feature explanatory power, typically this should be done after train/test split to mitigate risk of data leakage.

Correlation matrix

The correlation matrix indicates the following features with collinearity:

  • subscription_type and monthly_fee (1.0): The perfect correlation is expected since the monthly fee follows the type of subscription plan
  • avg_watch_time_per_day and watch_hours (0.35): A moderate correlation is reasonable as average watch time is in part driven by the number of hours watched; higher watch hours drives higher average watch time provided the same number of days watched
  • avg_watch_time_per_day and last_login_days (-0.34): A moderate negative correlation is somewhat unexpected and likely due to issues with synthetic data generation noted below

Remaining weaker correlations are generally between one-hot-encoded categorical features where some within-feature category correlation is expected.

# Create the correlation matrix
corr_df = temp_df.corr(method='pearson')
# Show correlation matrix in a heatmap
fig = px.imshow(corr_df, text_auto=True,
                title=f"Correlation matrix"       
                )
fig.update_layout(title_subtitle_text=f"Highly correlated features = yellow and blue")                
fig.show()


An auxillary view to illustrate the relationship between watch_hours, avg_watch_hours_per_day, and last_login_days is shown below.

Surprisingly, the linear relationship is weaker for greater lapses in days since last login. This indicates that despite having presumably less days to watch, subscribers who login infrequently are able notch high volumes of watch hours while somehow only watching very few hours per day. This is at odds with expectation since with fewer watch days, watch hours per day should increase but instead remains constant here. This illustrates potential pitfalls with synthetic data.

# Show scatterplot of `watch_hours`, `avg_watch_hours_per_day`, and `last_login_days`
fig = px.scatter(df, x='watch_hours', y='avg_watch_time_per_day', color='last_login_days',
                 title=f"Scatter plot of avg_watch_hours_per_day vs watch_hours")
fig.update_layout(title_subtitle_text=f"For greater lapses in login days, changes to watch hours increasingly has no affect <br>on daily watch hours despite an expecation for the opposite.") 
fig.show()

Variance inflation factor

Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) provides an alternate view in quantifying the extent that the variance of a regression coefficient is increased due to multicollearity. This is done by running multiple regressions with each independent variable as the target while the remainder serve as predictors. The resulting R-squared value from each of these auxiliary regressions is then used to calculate the VIF for the specific variable.

The VIF results below additionally identifies age as having high collinearity with other exogenous variables. Additionally, features that have inf values (or no bar) are also highly collinear - these collinear features align with our previous observations in the correlation matrix.

From here if we want to know what age is collinear with, we can further specify an auxiliary regression with age as an target (and all other features as predictors) to identify significant features. However we forgo this as age was previously shown to not be a statistically significant feature.

# Create function to calculate the VIF using statsmodel
def show_vif(df):
    vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
    vif_data["feature"] = df.columns
    vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(df.values, i) for i in range(df.shape[1])]
    return(vif_data.sort_values(by="VIF", ascending=False))
# Plot the VIF
vif_df = show_vif(temp_df)
fig = px.bar(vif_df, x='VIF', y='feature', color='VIF',
            title=f"Variance inflation factor"       
            )
fig.update_layout(
    title_subtitle_text=f"High multicollinearity = yellow (VIF > 5)",
    yaxis={'categoryorder':'total ascending'}
    )   
fig.show()

Multi-dimensional relationships

To summarize some of the high importance features we found during EDA in a compact visualization, we can make use of the parallel categories diagram (also known as parallel sets or alluvial diagram).

The diagram is particulary useful for multi-dimensional categorical data sets, where each categorical variable in the data set is represented by a column of rectangles and each rectangle is a discrete value within that variable. The relative heights of each rectangle represents the relative frequency of that discrete value within the variable.

In the parallel categories diagram below, we show last_login, engagement_grp, and churned together to show how typical subscribers that churn (white highlight) can be associated both with long lapses since last login time and low engagement levels (with watch hours of 5 hours or less).

# Plot the relationship between engagement_grp, last_login_grp, and churned
nf_palette = ['#B20710','#F5F5F1']
dims = ['last_login_grp', 'engagement_grp', 'churned']
fig = px.parallel_categories(df, dimensions=dims, color='churned',
                             color_continuous_scale=nf_palette,
                             color_continuous_midpoint=0.5,
                             height=600,
                             labels={'last_login_grp': 'Last Login (days)', 
                                     'engagement_grp': 'Engagement (hours watched)', 
                                     'churned': 'Churned'},
                             title=f"Relationship between engagement metrics and churn")
fig.update_layout(
    title_subtitle_text=f"Churn is driven by long lapses since last login and low engagement levels")
fig.update_traces(line_shape='hspline', selector=dict(type='parcats'))
fig.update_layout(xaxis=dict(showgrid=False))
fig.show()
